BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:AWS Virtual Meetup #5 - Chaos engineering
DTSTART;TZID=Europe/Paris:20200701T190000
DTEND;TZID=Europe/Paris:20200701T210000
UID:https://www.meetup.com/bordeaux-amazon-web-services/events/271494821/@
 community-events
DESCRIPTION:🔗 https://www.meetup.com/bordeaux-amazon-web-services/event
 s/271494821/\n\nHello all\,\nWe are very pleased to announce the fifth AWS
  virtual meetup 👐. This time we are going to play with the Cloud\, talk
 ing about Chaos Engineering. What exactly is Chaos\, how to create a relia
 ble system out of inherently unreliable parts. 🛑 For this meetup we all
  the talks will be in english given by international speakers!\nSee you on
  july 1st. Presentations will start at ⏰ 7:00 pm (Paris Time). Join us o
 nline 5 minutes before here: https://twitch.tv/sebAWS\n🎙 Talk 1: Fundam
 entals of Chaos Engineering and AWS reliability - Patrick Higgins - Gremli
 n - Level 100\nPatrick is a Chaos Engineer at Gremlin where he helps custo
 mers benefit from the power of controlled chaos. Join his session to get a
 n in-depth understanding of what Chaos Engineering is\, why it’s crucial
  to prevent outages\, and how you can use it to build resilience into your
  own systems.\n🎙 Talk 2: How to apply chaos engineering to serverless a
 pplications - Yan Cui - Lumigo.io - Level 200\nChaos engineering is a disc
 ipline that focuses on improving system resilience through controlled expe
 riments that expose the inherent chaos and failure modes in our system.\nY
 ou might have heard about tools such as Netflix's Simian Army or Gremlin\,
  which can inject different failures into your AWS environment to simulate
  different forms of infrastructure failures. But how can we apply the same
  principles to a serverless architecture where we have no access to the un
 derlying infrastructure? Can we adapt existing practices to expose the inh
 erent chaos in these systems? What are the limitations and new challenges 
 that we need to consider?\n🎙 Talk 3: Verification of serverless applica
 tions - Gunnar Grosch - Level 200/300\nThe transition into more complex sy
 stems is accelerating and the granularity in serverless applications makes
  even smaller systems complex and highly distributed. Join as we look at h
 ow to verify the output of the system through chaos engineering and the ad
 vantages established by CI/CD.\nGunnar is an AWS Serverless Hero and techn
 ical evangelist at Opsio. He has previously worked as both a frontend and 
 backend developer\, as an operations engineer within cloud infrastructure\
 , and as a technical trainer\, in addition to several different management
  roles.\n🎙 Talk 4: Continuous Resilience - Adrian Cockcroft - Level 200
 \nHow can we set everything so that we can be sure that the resilience we 
 want is continuously available\, and our backup plans will work when we ne
 ed them.\n\nCommunauté: aws-bordeaux\n💻 Événement en ligne
TZID:Europe/Paris
